.TH opendmarc-reports 8 "The Trusted Domain Project"
.SH NAME
.B opendmarc-reports
\- OpenDMARC aggregate and forensic report generation tool
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B opendmarc-reports
[options]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B opendmarc-reports
operates in one of two modes.
.PP
In the default aggregate mode, it pulls data from an OpenDMARC database and
generates periodic DMARC aggregate (RUA) reports.  The database is populated
by a running
.B opendmarc-import(8)
on a message history file generated by an
.B opendmarc(8)
filter as messages arrive and are processed.  This includes the collection
of reporting URIs, which this script uses to make reports available to those
that request them.
.PP
In forensic mode (see
.IR --forensic ),
the script reads a pre-formed AFRF failure report from standard input and
injects it via SMTP, acting as a drop-in replacement for
.I sendmail -t
as the milter's
.I ReportCommand.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.I --config=file
Read configuration from
.I file
instead of the default
.IR @sysconfdir@/opendmarc/opendmarc-reports.conf .
The file contains one
.I key = value
entry per line; keys are the long option names without the leading
.IR -- .
Boolean options accept
.IR 1 / yes / true
or
.IR 0 / no / false .
Lines beginning with
.B #
are treated as comments.  Command-line arguments always take precedence
over config file settings.  This file is read whether the script is
invoked from cron or by the milter as
.IR ReportCommand ,
so SMTP credentials configured here apply to both aggregate and forensic
reports without exposing them in
.IR opendmarc.conf .
.TP
.I --day
Generate reports on day boundaries.  Overrides the value of
.I --interval
(see below).
.TP
.I --dbscheme=scheme
Specify "msyql" (the default) or "MariaDB".
.TP
.I --dbhost=hostname
Specifies the hostname on which the SQL server is running.  Defaults to
the value of the environment variable OPENDMARC_DBHOST, or "localhost" if
the environment variable is not set.
.TP
.I --dbname=name
Specifies the SQL database name to be accessed.  Defaults to
the value of the environment variable OPENDMARC_DB, or "opendmarc" if
the environment variable is not set.
.TP
.I --dbpasswd=password
Specifies the password for the SQL database to be accessed.  Defaults to
the value of the environment variable OPENDMARC_PASSWORD, or "opendmarc" if
the environment variable is not set.
.TP
.I --dbport=port
Specifies the TCP port on which the SQL server is expected to be listening.
Defaults to the value of the environment variable OPENDMARC_PORT, or 3306
if the environment variable is not set.
.TP
.I --dbuser=user
Specifies the SQL user to be used to access the database.  Defaults to
the value of the environment variable OPENDMARC_USER, or "opendmarc" if
the environment variable is not set.
.TP
.I --domain=name
Generates a report (if one is due) for the named domain, rather than checking
all of them.
.TP
.I --forensic
Switches to forensic (failure) report mode.  Instead of querying the database
and generating aggregate reports, the script reads a pre-formed AFRF
(Auth Failure Reporting Format) message from standard input and injects it
via SMTP.  This mode is intended for use as the milter's
.I ReportCommand
value, e.g.:
.sp
.in +4n
ReportCommand /usr/sbin/opendmarc-reports \\
    --forensic --smtp-server=relay.example.com
.in
.sp
The SMTP envelope sender is taken from
.I --report-email
(or its default).  Envelope recipients are extracted from the
.IR To: ,
.IR Cc: ,
and
.I Bcc:
headers of the message on standard input, replicating the behaviour of
.IR "sendmail -t" .
.TP
.I --help
Prints a help message and terminates.
.TP
.I --interval=secs
Generates reports only for hosts that have not had a report generated in
at least the last
.I secs
seconds.
.TP
.I --keepfiles
Instructs the script to keep the XML report files in the current directory
after sending.  Implied by
.IR --test .
.TP
.I --nodomain=name
Skips generating a report for the named domain.  Can be specified multiple
times to skip multiple reporting domains.
.TP
.I --skipdomains=file
Reads a list of domain names from
.I file
(one per line, comments introduced by
.BR # )
and skips generating reports for any domain in the list.  Equivalent to
specifying
.B --nodomain
for each entry in the file.
.TP
.I --noupdate
Suppresses marking the time of the transmission of the report in the database.
Normally this would be done to prevent reports from being sent too close
together.  Implied by
.IR --test .
.TP
.I --report-contact=addr
Specifies the contact address written into the
.I <email>
element of the
.I <report_metadata>
block in aggregate reports (RFC 9990 section 3.1.1.3: "Contact to use when
contacting the Reporting Organization").  If not set, the value of
.I --report-email
is used.  This allows the metadata contact address to differ from the
SMTP envelope sender when required.
.TP
.I --report-email=addr
Generates reports using the specified address as the SMTP envelope sender
and the
.I From:
header of outgoing report messages.  In
.I --forensic
mode this address is also used as the MAIL FROM.  When
.I --verp
is enabled the address is further encoded per recipient.  The default is
"postmaster@HOSTNAME" where HOSTNAME is replaced by the hostname of the
host generating the report.  See also
.IR --report-contact .
.TP
.I --report-org=domain
Generates reports using the specified domain name as the organization
responsible for the report.  This is used to create the archive filename
and is included in the report content.  The default is the hostname of
the host generating the report.
.TP
.I --smtp-server=host
Causes reports to be sent by transmitting them using SMTP to the named
.I host,
which can be an IP address or a hostname.  Defaults to the value of the
environment variable OPENDMARC_SMTPSERVER, or "127.0.0.1" if the
environment variable is not set.
.TP
.I --smtp-port=port
Causes reports to be sent by transmitting them using SMTP to the specified
.IR port .
Defaults to the value of the environment variable OPENDMARC_SMTPPORT,
or 25 if the environment variable is not set.
.TP
.I --stale-check
Before sending each report, query the StaleMARC RBL to determine whether the
target domain or RUA/RUF address has known delivery problems.  Reports are
suppressed for listed entries.  On lookup failure the script fails open and
proceeds with sending.  Applies to both aggregate and forensic modes.
See also
.I --stale-def-deny
and
.IR --stale-server .
.TP
.I --stale-def-deny
Use the default-deny variants of the StaleMARC RBL endpoints
.RI ( checkDomainDefDeny.php
and
.IR checkRuaDefDeny.php ).
In this mode, domains and addresses that have not yet been tested by StaleMARC
are also treated as stale and suppressed.  Has no effect unless
.I --stale-check
is also set.
.TP
.I --stale-server=url
Override the base URL for the StaleMARC RBL API.  The default is
.IR https://stalemarc.measurement.network/api .
Has no effect unless
.I --stale-check
is also set.
.TP
.I --test, -n
Dry-run mode.  Reports are generated but not transmitted, and the database
is not updated.  Implies
.I --keepfiles
and
.IR --noupdate .
.TP
.I --utc
Instructs the database to change to the UTC timezone when generating output.
Otherwise, the database default is used.
.TP
.I --keepfiles
Keep the generated XML report files in the local directory rather than
deleting them after sending.
.TP
.I --test (-n)
Do not send reports.  Implies
.I --keepfiles
and
.I --noupdate.
.TP
.I --verbose
Increase the amount of verbosity written to standard error.  May be repeated
for further detail.
.TP
.I --verp
Use Variable Envelope Return Paths (VERP) when sending reports.  The SMTP
MAIL FROM address is encoded with the recipient address so that bounces
identify the specific destination that failed, e.g.:
.sp
.in +4n
postmaster+dmarc-rua=example.com@reporter.example.com
.in
.sp
In forensic mode, enabling VERP causes one SMTP transaction to be issued
per recipient rather than grouping all recipients into a single transaction.
.TP
.I --version
Print version number and exit.
.SH REPORTING SUPPRESSIONS
The script checks the
.I suppressions
database table before sending each report.  If the destination RUA/RUF
address, or its domain, appears in that table the report is silently
skipped.  The table is also checked at the domain level, so adding a bare
domain name (e.g.
.IR example.com )
suppresses all reports for that domain regardless of their destination
address.
.PP
The table is loaded once at startup and is not queried per-message, so
changes take effect on the next run.  If the table does not exist (e.g. on
a pre-migration install) the check is skipped and a notice is written to
standard error at verbosity level 2.
.PP
Entries can be inserted manually:
.sp
.in +4n
INSERT INTO suppressions (address, reason)
    VALUES ('dmarc@example.com', 'manual');
.in
.sp
When
.I --verp
is enabled, DMARC report bounces return to an encoded envelope sender
that identifies the failing address.  A bounce-processing script can
decode that address and insert it into this table automatically, building
a locally-maintained suppression list informed by real delivery failures.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B OPENDMARC_DBHOST
Default value for
.IR --dbhost .
.TP
.B OPENDMARC_DB
Default value for
.IR --dbname .
.TP
.B OPENDMARC_PASSWORD
Default value for
.IR --dbpasswd .
.TP
.B OPENDMARC_PORT
Default value for
.IR --dbport .
.TP
.B OPENDMARC_USER
Default value for
.IR --dbuser .
.TP
.B OPENDMARC_SMTPSERVER
Default value for
.IR --smtp-server .
.TP
.B OPENDMARC_SMTPPORT
Default value for
.IR --smtp-port .
.SH VERSION
This man page covers the version of
.I opendmarc-reports
that shipped with version @VERSION@ of
.IR OpenDMARC .
